A fall nighttime electrofishing Targeted Survey was conducted at Washington Lake on September 22, 2022 to evaluate young of the year Walleye (YOY) and yearling Walleye (YRL) abundance. A total of 127 YOY were sampled for a catch rate of 95.3/hour, which was the fifth highest catch rate ever recorded at Washington and was within the lake's historical fourth quartile (> 79.8). The 2022 year class appears strong in abundance. In 2022, the mean length for YOY was 7.6 inches, which was within Washington's historical third quartile (6.9 to 7.6), indicating moderate growth (within the inter-quartile range) for this lake. In 2022, no yearlings were sampled.

STATUS OF THE FISHERY:
Present walleye population is composed mainly of three age groups, III's, IV's, and V's with no single age group present in overwhelmingly greater numbers. Growth is average with no sign of either stunting or excessive growth present. Spawning area is fair with several areas of the lake suitable for walleye as well as other species of game fish. With the exception of N. Pike, all specie of game and rough fish were caught in greater numbers than the statewide averages. N. Pike appear to be somewhat below state averages. N. Pike growth rate was average or slightly better. Bluegill appeared to be slightly stunted in growth.

Fall night-time electrofishing was conducted at Washington Lake in 2017 to evaluate young of the year Walleye (YWAE) and yearling Walleye (YRLWAE) abundance. Electrofishing sampled 119 YWAE for a catch rate of 51.0/hour. The 2017 YWAE year class would likely be considered moderate in size. Young of the year Walleye had an average length of 6.0 inches indicating that growth was slow this year for Washington Lake. The latest stocking regime (2,266,000 fry every other year) was initiated in 1991. Catch rates, for YWAE, from 1993 to 2017 (n=22) ranged from 0.0 to 126.2/hour with an average of 43.1. Catch rates from stocked years (n=12) ranged from 1.1 to 108.8/hour with an average of 61.5. Catch rates from non-stocked years (n=10) ranged from 0.0 to 126.2/hour with an average of 21.1. With a mean that was almost three times higher, fry stocking is having a positive influence on YWAE abundance at Washington Lake. However, a definitive answer cannot be reached because of the inability to differentiate stocked fish from naturally reproduced fish during years when Walleye fry are stocked. Of interest, the highest fall electrofishing catch rate ever recorded at Washington (126.2/hour) occurred during a non-stocked year (1998). Natural reproduction during non-stocked years was documented 8 out of 10 times (80%), but only one of those YWAE year classes (1998) was considered to be exceptionally strong (126.2/hour). It is likely that stocking would be required to maintain a quality Walleye fishery at Washington Lake. Electrofishing sampled low numbers (9) of YRLWAE for a catch rate 3.9/hour, likely indicating that the 2016 year class was still weak. In 2017, the YRLWAE mean length was 12.5 inches, indicating fast growth. Washington was designated as being infested with Zebra Mussel in 2015.

A targeted survey (fall nighttime electrofishing) was conducted on Lake Washington on October 4th, 2023, to evaluate young of the year (YOY) and yearling Walleye abundance. A total of 89 YOY were sampled for a catch rate of 66.8 fish/hr, which was above the lake's historical median (33.8 fish/hr). In 2023, the average length for YOY was 5.2 inches, which was the shortest average on record and was below Washington's historical average (6.9 inches). Walleye fry were stocked this year. In 2023, a total of 4 yearlings were sampled for a catch rate of 3.0 fish/hr, which was above Washington's historical median (2.6 fish/hr). The average length for the yearlings was 11.8 inches and was slightly above Washington's historical average (11.7 inches).

STATUS OF THE FISHERY:

FISHES PRESENT:
Common sucker, carp, northern spottail shiner, pugnose shiner, northern mimic shiner, brassy minnow, bluntnose minnow, northern fathead minnow, northern black bullhead, northern brown bullhead, northern yellow bullhead, western banded killifish, perch, walleye, Iowa darter, largemouth bass, bluegill, black crappie, brook stickleback, western golden shiner, scaly johnny darter, green sunfish, white crappie.

HOOPNET CATCH (POUNDS/SET):
Carp (2.731), black bullhead (0.150), brown bullhead (0.014), yellow bullhead (0.132), walleye (0.025), bluegill (0.058), green sunfish (0.004), bluegill x green (0.003), white crappie (0.201), perch (0.002), common sucker (0.048), and largemouth bass (0.025). The level of abundance is very low for all species, except the carp and white crappie.

COMPARISONS WITH PREVIOUS SURVEYS:
The test seining in 1940 and the survey in 1938 both showed bullheads to be very numerous. In 1947, after 10 years of removal operations they were very low. Carp were abundant in all three investigations. Perch were abundant in 1938, but very low in 1947. Panfishes, with the exception of the crappies were low in all the surveys. Crappies were abundant in 1940 and 1947. The water was found to be turbid in all three surveys. The maximum depth in 1938 was 15 feet and in 1947 was 20 feet due to a rise in water levels. No change in the general abundance of aquatic plants was noted.

A resurvey was conducted at Washington in 2014 to monitor the lake's physical, chemical, and biological characteristics. In 2014, a total of 14 species, plus hybrid sunfish, were sampled in the gill nets and trap nets.

Submergent vegetation was unusually plentiful in 2014. Plant transect sampling documented 16 varieties of submergent vegetation, of which 5 (Bushy Pondweed, Clasping-leaf Pondweed, Illinois Pondweed, Variable-leaf Pondweed, and Water Celery) were rated as common. During the last resurvey in 2004, Eurasian Watermilfoil (aquatic invasive plant species) was the only submergent vegetation variety ranked as common, with dense beds being found across much of the lake. Only one small fragment of Eurasian Watermilfoil was found floating, between two transects, during the 2014 survey. The reason for this drastic change in abundance was unknown. Chara, a type of advanced algae that has a musky odor, was also rated as being common and occurred at 98% of the vegetation transects. The maximum depth at which rooted vegetation was found was 9.6 feet. Sand and silt were the most plentiful shoalwater substrates, and both were rated as being common. The lake was well mixed on 7/28/14, with oxygen near the surface being 8.2 mg/l and 7.8 mg/l just off the bottom. Water clarity was poor to fair (3.0') due to an algae bloom. Washington's lakeshed was large (22,578 acres) and dominated by row crop agriculture (corn and soybeans). The lakeshed to lake ratio was 9:1. Washington's shoreline was heavily developed with homes, cabins, and trailers accounting for roughly 85% of the entire shoreline.

Gill nets sampled moderate numbers of Walleye (125) for a catch rate of 8.3/net, which was within the normal range for a lake of this type. The 2012 catch rate was similar at 9.5/net. Catch rates from 1951 to 2014 (n=14) were variable, ranging from 2.2 to 41.2/net with an average of 14.2. The latest stocking regime of 1,000 fry/littoral acre (acres less than 15 feet deep) every other year was initiated in 1991. Gill net catch rates during this regime (1999, 2001, 2004, 2008, 2012, and 2014) ranged from 5.8 to 19.0/net with an average of 12.4. In 2014, gill netted Walleye were 9.5 to 24.5 inches long with an average of 16.3. Approximately 62% of the gill net sample was 17 inches or longer, indicating a quality size distribution. In 2014, Walleye were age-1 through age-13 with eleven year-classes being represented. In the gill nets, age-1 and age-3 fish made up approximately 32% and 47% of the catch, respectively. The 2011 year-class was the only year-class that would be considered strong, but the 2013 year-class was also substantial in size. The contribution from non-stocked years, to the total catch in 2014, was only 6% of the gill net aged fish. It was unknown what portion of the stocked year fish came from natural reproduction or stocking. Contribution from non-stocked years, from the latest six assessments (1999-2014) ranged from 6% to 36% of the gill net catch, averaging 19.5%, indicating that over 80% of the fish sampled matched up with years when fry were stocked. Analysis of gill net age data from the 1991 to 2014 assessments (n=8) indicated that only 1 strong year-class (2006) was produced during a non-stocked year (n=11). This likely meant that the Washington Lake Walleye fishery was dependent upon stocking. In 2014, Walleye reached 16.1 inches in length after three years of growth. This data indicated that growth was fast.

Gill nets sampled low numbers of Northern Pike (52) for a catch rate of 3.5/net, which was slightly below the normal range for a lake of this type. The 2012 catch rate was similar, at 3.8/net. Catch rates from 1951 to 2014 (n=14) were mostly low, ranging from 0.0 to 8.5/net with an average of 3.2. This indicated that recruitment was poor most years at Washington Lake. Northern Pike were 7.9 to 33.9 inches long with an average of 23.0. Fish that were aged were age-0 to age-4 with four age-classes being present. Growth was typical for Washington Lake Northern Pike. Approximately 92% of the gill net catch was between 21.0 and 26.9 inches in length.

Gill nets sampled low numbers of Yellow Perch (63) for a catch rate of 4.2/net, which was just inside the normal range for this type of lake. The 2012 catch rate was over 10 times lower at 0.4/net. Catch rates from 1951 to 2014 (n=14) were generally low, ranging from 0.2 to 54.7/net with an average of 12.5. Yellow perch were 4.4 to 6.5 inches long with an average of 5.8. Yellow Perch ages were estimated to be age-1, age-2, and age-3. Age-2 fish accounted for 97% of the gill net sample, indicating inconsistent recruitment. Growth was slightly below the Washington Lake 20 year average.

Trap nets failed to sample any Black Crappie in 2014. This was the lowest catch rate ever recorded since trap netting began in 1951. The 2012 catch rate was also very low (0.6/net). Catch rates from 1951 to 2014 (n=13) were mostly low, ranging from 0 to 22.6/net with an average of 4.0. Gill nets sampled low numbers of Black Crappie (18) for a catch rate of 1.2/net, which was within the normal range for this lake type. The 2014 gill net catch rate was the lowest on record. Catch rates from 1957 to 2014 (n=13) were generally low, ranging from 1.2 to 11.4/net with an average of 5.0. Gill netted black crappie were 5.0 to 13.5 inches long with an average of 9.5.

Trap nets sampled moderate numbers of Bluegill (142) for a catch rate of 9.5/net which was within the normal range for this type of lake. The 2012 catch rate was 17.0/net. Catch rates from 1951 to 2014 (n=13) ranged from 0.2 to 23.9/net, with an average of 12.0. In 2014, trap netted bluegill were 1.9 to 7.3 inches long with an average of 4.6. Only 3% (4 fish) of the trap net catch was 7 inches or longer, indicating a poor size structure. Approximately 15% of the trap net catch was 6 inches or longer.

Spring night-time electrofishing, targeting Largemouth Bass, sampled low to moderate numbers (27) of fish for a catch rate of 11.6/hr. The 2012 catch rate was 17.3/hr. Historic catch rates (n=8) were variable, ranging from 8.7 to 40.1/hr with an average of 17.4. Largemouth bass were 12.8 to 19.1 inches long with an average of 15.3. Approximately 93% of the electrofishing catch was between 13.0 and 17.9 inches long, which should appeal to Largemouth Bass anglers. Electrofishing on Washington may not be as effective as it is on other lakes, due to an abundance of offshore submergent vegetation. Anecdotal reports from bass fishing clubs mention Washington Lake as having a quality Largemouth Bass fishery.

Gill nets sampled moderate numbers of Smallmouth Bass (41) for a catch rate of 2.7/net, which was within the normal range for this type of lake. The 2014 catch rate was the highest ever recorded at Washington Lake. The 2012 catch rate was at 1.3/net. Catch rates from 1951 to 2014 (n=14) were mostly low ranging from 0.0 to 2.7/net with an average of 0.6. Relative abundance increased dramatically in the 2000's, when compared to the 1950's through the 1990's. Gill netted smallmouth bass were 14.5 to 19.5 inches long with an average of 16.4. Approximately 93% of the gill net sample was 15 inches or longer, indicating a high quality size structure. Spring night time electrofishing sampled low numbers (4) of Smallmouth Bass, as is usually the case at Washington, for a catch rate of 1.7/hr. The 2012 catch rate was 9.4/hr. Historic spring electrofishing catch rates (n=8) were mostly low, ranging from 0.4 to 9.4/hr with an average of 3.8. Electrofished Smallmouth Bass were 10.0 to 16.6 inches long with an average of 13.9. Gill netting, electrofishing, and trap netting (1 @ 6.5 inches in length) sampled a wide range of lengths of Smallmouth Bass, indicating that a somewhat healthy population was present. Recruitment did not appear to be consistent every year, based on the size range data.

Gill nets sampled low numbers of Channel Catfish (1) for a catch rate of 0.1/net. This was the second time that Channel Catfish were sampled in Washington Lake. One additional Channel Catfish was sampled at Washington, in 2012. The 2014 fish was 22.9 inches long. It was unknown how this fish ended up in Washington Lake, but it likely immigrated up Washington Creek and swam over the outlet dam during a high water event. Water levels were exceptionally high during the spring of 2011 and in June of 2014.

Trap nets sampled low numbers of Common Carp (1) for a catch rate of 0.1/net, which was below the normal range for this type of lake. The 2014 catch rate tied the record low from 2008. Historic catch rates (n=13) were generally low, ranging from 0.1 to 15.7/net with an average of 2.4. Trap net catch rates have been below the normal range since the 1979 survey. Gill nets sampled 3 Common Carp for a catch rate of 0.2/net which was below the normal range for this lake type. Historic gill net catch rates, dating back to 1957, ranged from 0.0 to 1.4/net with an average of 0.6. Gill netted Common Carp were 22.2 to 32.1 inches long with an average of 25.8.

Gill nets sampled low numbers of Black Bullhead (27) for a catch rate of 1.8/net, which was below the normal range for this type of lake, as was the 2012 catch rate (0.8/net). The last time that Black Bullhead were sampled in higher numbers was in the 2004 assessment (51.2/gill net). Historic catch rates from 1951 through 2014 (n=14) were generally low, ranging from 0.0 to 51.2/net with an average of 7.4. Black Bullhead were 10.5 to 15.0 inches long with an average of 13.1. Black Bullhead were not sampled in trap nets in 2014, which tied the record low from 1951. Historic Black Bullhead trap net catch rates have been below the normal range 10 out-of 12 times (83%) at Washington Lake.

Additional species sampled in the standard gear included Bowfin (5), Hybrid Sunfish (6), Pumpkinseed Sunfish (2), White Sucker (5), and Yellow Bullhead (18).
